  • Field Details

    • SHOW_PASSED_TEST_CASES

      public static boolean SHOW_PASSED_TEST_CASES
      A static attribute that tells the autograder to display test cases that passed. Setting this to false in the concrete class constructors will tell the autograder to hide your passed tests and only show failed test cases. This is experimental and may not be implemented in the autograder.

    • INDEX_OUT_OF_RANGE

      public static final String INDEX_OUT_OF_RANGE
      A constant string used to indicate that an operation failed because it wanted to access a list element that did not exist. We use this to ensure that the code does not crash with java.lang.ArrayIndexOutOfBoundsException
      See Also:

    • get

      public abstract String get(int position)
      Returns (but does not remove) the string at the given position.
      Parameters:
      position - is the position of the string that is retrieved.
      Returns:
      The string at the given position. If the position was not a valid list position then returns INDEX_OUT_OF_RANGE.

    • set

      public abstract String set(int position, String element)
      Sets the list element at the given position.

      Changes the value (string) of the list element at the given position and returns the original value (string)

      Parameters:
      position - specifies the location in the list whose value will be changed.
      element - specifies the new value that the list element at the given position will have.
      Returns:
      Returns the string that was initially in location position. If the position was not a valid list position then returns INDEX_OUT_OF_RANGE.

    • add

      public abstract String add(int position, String element)
      Adds a new string to the given location of the list.

      Adds a new string to the list at the given position. In order to successfully add a new item to the list, the position must satisfy 0 invalid input: '<'= position invalid input: '<'= this.size() If this is not satisfied, then the method simply returns INDEX_OUT_OF_RANGE. If this is satisfied, it adds the new string and returns INDEX_OK.

      Parameters:
      position - specifies the location in the list where the new element will be added.
      element - specifies string that is being added at the given position will have.
      Returns:
      If the input position was valid then returns INDEX_OK. Otherwise, returns INDEX_OUT_OF_RANGE.

    • remove

      public abstract String remove(int position)
      Removes the string at a given location from the list and returns it.

      Removes the string in the list at the given position. If that items exists, the method removes and returns it. If there is no string with the given position, the list is left unchanged and returns INDEX_OUT_OF_RANGE.

      Parameters:
      position - specifies the position of the string to remove.
      Returns:
      the string that was removed from the list if it existed, otherwise returns INDEX_OUT_OF_RANGE.

    • commonStrings

      public abstract SList commonStrings()
      Finds the strings that appear the most times in this list.

      There may be zero, one or more than one string that appears the most times in this list. The method returns a new list that contains these strings.

      For example, if this is empty, then there are no strings that appear the most times.

      If the list is ["cat", "dog", "cat", "eel", "dog"] then the method should return the list ["cat", "dog"].

      Returns:
      a list containing the strings that appear the most times in this list.

    • commonStrings

      public abstract SList[] commonStrings(int n)
      Finds the strings that appear the most times in this list.

      Instead of returning a list of the strings that appear the MOST, this returns n lists, that contain the MOST, Second MOST, ..., n-th MOST frequently appearing strings in this list.

      Examples: If the list is ["A", "A", "A", "B", "B", "C", "C", "D"] then commonString(1) will return [["A"]] (a list with 1 list in it), and commonString(2) will return the list [["A"], ["B","C"]], and commonString(3) will return the list [["A"], ["B","C"], ["D"]]. Note that commonString(6) will also return the list [["A"], ["B","C"], ["D"]]. If data cannot produce n lists then it returns as many as possible.

      Parameters:
      n - is the number of lists of commonly used words. n must be at least 1.
      Returns:
      a list of lists of the n most commonly appearing strings in this list. If n is larger than the actual number of lists that can be generated then returns a list of lists with as many lists as possible.
